[
    {
        "index": 1,
        "start_time": 6842,
        "end_time": 11668,
        "text": "Many of the inanimate objects around you\nprobably seem perfectly still."
    },
    {
        "index": 2,
        "start_time": 11668,
        "end_time": 15663,
        "text": "But look deep into the atomic structure\nof any of them,"
    },
    {
        "index": 3,
        "start_time": 15663,
        "end_time": 18333,
        "text": "and you&#39;ll see a world in constant flux."
    },
    {
        "index": 4,
        "start_time": 18333,
        "end_time": 19138,
        "text": "Stretching,"
    },
    {
        "index": 5,
        "start_time": 19138,
        "end_time": 20067,
        "text": "contracting,"
    },
    {
        "index": 6,
        "start_time": 20067,
        "end_time": 21002,
        "text": "springing,"
    },
    {
        "index": 7,
        "start_time": 21002,
        "end_time": 21977,
        "text": "jittering,"
    },
    {
        "index": 8,
        "start_time": 21977,
        "end_time": 25158,
        "text": "drifting atoms everywhere."
    },
    {
        "index": 9,
        "start_time": 25158,
        "end_time": 28355,
        "text": "And though that movement may seem chaotic,\nit&#39;s not random."
    },
    {
        "index": 10,
        "start_time": 28355,
        "end_time": 29890,
        "text": "Atoms that are bonded together,"
    },
    {
        "index": 11,
        "start_time": 29890,
        "end_time": 32269,
        "text": "and that describes almost all substances,"
    },
    {
        "index": 12,
        "start_time": 32269,
        "end_time": 34881,
        "text": "move according to a set of principles."
    },
    {
        "index": 13,
        "start_time": 34881,
        "end_time": 39776,
        "text": "For example, take molecules,\natoms held together by covalent bonds."
    },
    {
        "index": 14,
        "start_time": 39776,
        "end_time": 42322,
        "text": "There are three basic ways \nmolecules can move:"
    },
    {
        "index": 15,
        "start_time": 42322,
        "end_time": 43214,
        "text": "rotation,"
    },
    {
        "index": 16,
        "start_time": 43214,
        "end_time": 44337,
        "text": "translation,"
    },
    {
        "index": 17,
        "start_time": 44337,
        "end_time": 45886,
        "text": "and vibration."
    },
    {
        "index": 18,
        "start_time": 45886,
        "end_time": 49038,
        "text": "Rotation and translation \nmove a molecule in space"
    },
    {
        "index": 19,
        "start_time": 49038,
        "end_time": 52166,
        "text": "while its atoms stay \nthe same distance apart."
    },
    {
        "index": 20,
        "start_time": 52166,
        "end_time": 55608,
        "text": "Vibration, on the other hand, \nchanges those distances,"
    },
    {
        "index": 21,
        "start_time": 55608,
        "end_time": 58250,
        "text": "actually altering the molecule&#39;s shape."
    },
    {
        "index": 22,
        "start_time": 58250,
        "end_time": 62688,
        "text": "For any molecule, you can count up\nthe number of different ways it can move."
    },
    {
        "index": 23,
        "start_time": 62688,
        "end_time": 65304,
        "text": "That corresponds to \nits degrees of freedom,"
    },
    {
        "index": 24,
        "start_time": 65304,
        "end_time": 66941,
        "text": "which in the context of mechanics"
    },
    {
        "index": 25,
        "start_time": 66941,
        "end_time": 70450,
        "text": "basically means the number of variables\nwe need to take into account"
    },
    {
        "index": 26,
        "start_time": 70450,
        "end_time": 73345,
        "text": "to understand the full system."
    },
    {
        "index": 27,
        "start_time": 73345,
        "end_time": 78019,
        "text": "Three-dimensional space is defined by\nx, y, and z axes."
    },
    {
        "index": 28,
        "start_time": 78019,
        "end_time": 83034,
        "text": "Translation allows the molecule to move\nin the direction of any of them."
    },
    {
        "index": 29,
        "start_time": 83034,
        "end_time": 85098,
        "text": "That&#39;s three degrees of freedom."
    },
    {
        "index": 30,
        "start_time": 85098,
        "end_time": 88758,
        "text": "It can also rotate around \nany of these three axes."
    },
    {
        "index": 31,
        "start_time": 88758,
        "end_time": 89990,
        "text": "That&#39;s three more,"
    },
    {
        "index": 32,
        "start_time": 89990,
        "end_time": 93042,
        "text": "unless it&#39;s a linear molecule, \nlike carbon dioxide."
    },
    {
        "index": 33,
        "start_time": 93042,
        "end_time": 97457,
        "text": "There, one of the rotations just spins\nthe molecule around its own axis,"
    },
    {
        "index": 34,
        "start_time": 97457,
        "end_time": 101607,
        "text": "which doesn&#39;t count because it doesn&#39;t\nchange the position of the atoms."
    },
    {
        "index": 35,
        "start_time": 101607,
        "end_time": 104596,
        "text": "Vibration is where it gets a bit tricky."
    },
    {
        "index": 36,
        "start_time": 104596,
        "end_time": 106979,
        "text": "Let&#39;s take a simple molecule,\nlike hydrogen."
    },
    {
        "index": 37,
        "start_time": 106979,
        "end_time": 111682,
        "text": "The length of the bond that holds the two\natoms together is constantly changing"
    },
    {
        "index": 38,
        "start_time": 111682,
        "end_time": 114479,
        "text": "as if the atoms were connected \nby a spring."
    },
    {
        "index": 39,
        "start_time": 114479,
        "end_time": 118985,
        "text": "That change in distance is tiny,\nless than a billionth of a meter."
    },
    {
        "index": 40,
        "start_time": 118985,
        "end_time": 123791,
        "text": "The more atoms and bonds a molecule has,\nthe more vibrational modes."
    },
    {
        "index": 41,
        "start_time": 123791,
        "end_time": 126816,
        "text": "For example, a water molecule \nhas three atoms:"
    },
    {
        "index": 42,
        "start_time": 126816,
        "end_time": 130164,
        "text": "one oxygen and two hydrogens,\nand two bonds."
    },
    {
        "index": 43,
        "start_time": 130164,
        "end_time": 132476,
        "text": "That gives it three modes of vibration:"
    },
    {
        "index": 44,
        "start_time": 132476,
        "end_time": 133824,
        "text": "symmetric stretching,"
    },
    {
        "index": 45,
        "start_time": 133824,
        "end_time": 135408,
        "text": "asymmetric stretching,"
    },
    {
        "index": 46,
        "start_time": 135408,
        "end_time": 136896,
        "text": "and bending."
    },
    {
        "index": 47,
        "start_time": 136896,
        "end_time": 141142,
        "text": "More complicated molecules have even\nfancier vibrational modes,"
    },
    {
        "index": 48,
        "start_time": 141142,
        "end_time": 142426,
        "text": "like rocking,"
    },
    {
        "index": 49,
        "start_time": 142426,
        "end_time": 143607,
        "text": "wagging,"
    },
    {
        "index": 50,
        "start_time": 143607,
        "end_time": 145195,
        "text": "and twisting."
    },
    {
        "index": 51,
        "start_time": 145195,
        "end_time": 149854,
        "text": "If you know how many atoms a molecule has,\nyou can count its vibrational modes."
    },
    {
        "index": 52,
        "start_time": 149854,
        "end_time": 152011,
        "text": "Start with the total degrees of freedom,"
    },
    {
        "index": 53,
        "start_time": 152011,
        "end_time": 155427,
        "text": "which is three times the number\nof atoms in the molecule."
    },
    {
        "index": 54,
        "start_time": 155427,
        "end_time": 158837,
        "text": "That&#39;s because each atom can move\nin three different directions."
    },
    {
        "index": 55,
        "start_time": 158837,
        "end_time": 161393,
        "text": "Three of the total correspond \nto translation"
    },
    {
        "index": 56,
        "start_time": 161393,
        "end_time": 164633,
        "text": "when all the atoms \nare going in the same direction."
    },
    {
        "index": 57,
        "start_time": 164633,
        "end_time": 169430,
        "text": "And three, or two for linear molecules,\ncorrespond to rotations."
    },
    {
        "index": 58,
        "start_time": 169430,
        "end_time": 173999,
        "text": "All the rest, 3N-6\nor 3N-5 for linear molecules,"
    },
    {
        "index": 59,
        "start_time": 173999,
        "end_time": 176127,
        "text": "are vibrations."
    },
    {
        "index": 60,
        "start_time": 176127,
        "end_time": 177961,
        "text": "So what&#39;s causing all this motion?"
    },
    {
        "index": 61,
        "start_time": 177961,
        "end_time": 182053,
        "text": "Molecules move because they absorb\nenergy from their surroundings,"
    },
    {
        "index": 62,
        "start_time": 182053,
        "end_time": 185748,
        "text": "mainly in the form of heat\nor electromagnetic radiation."
    },
    {
        "index": 63,
        "start_time": 185748,
        "end_time": 188355,
        "text": "When this energy gets transferred\nto the molecules,"
    },
    {
        "index": 64,
        "start_time": 188355,
        "end_time": 189415,
        "text": "they vibrate,"
    },
    {
        "index": 65,
        "start_time": 189415,
        "end_time": 190221,
        "text": "rotate,"
    },
    {
        "index": 66,
        "start_time": 190221,
        "end_time": 192507,
        "text": "or translate faster."
    },
    {
        "index": 67,
        "start_time": 192507,
        "end_time": 196534,
        "text": "Faster motion increases the kinetic energy\nof the molecules and atoms."
    },
    {
        "index": 68,
        "start_time": 196534,
        "end_time": 200792,
        "text": "We define this as an increase \nin temperature and thermal energy."
    },
    {
        "index": 69,
        "start_time": 200792,
        "end_time": 205445,
        "text": "This is the phenomenon your microwave oven\nuses to heat your food."
    },
    {
        "index": 70,
        "start_time": 205445,
        "end_time": 209247,
        "text": "The oven emits microwave radiation,\nwhich is absorbed by the molecules,"
    },
    {
        "index": 71,
        "start_time": 209247,
        "end_time": 211723,
        "text": "especially those of water."
    },
    {
        "index": 72,
        "start_time": 211723,
        "end_time": 213659,
        "text": "They move around faster and faster,"
    },
    {
        "index": 73,
        "start_time": 213659,
        "end_time": 218101,
        "text": "bumping into each other and increasing\nthe food&#39;s temperature and thermal energy."
    },
    {
        "index": 74,
        "start_time": 218101,
        "end_time": 220513,
        "text": "The greenhouse effect is another example."
    },
    {
        "index": 75,
        "start_time": 220513,
        "end_time": 223250,
        "text": "Some of the solar radiation \nthat hits the Earth&#39;s surface"
    },
    {
        "index": 76,
        "start_time": 223250,
        "end_time": 225605,
        "text": "is reflected back to the atmosphere."
    },
    {
        "index": 77,
        "start_time": 225605,
        "end_time": 231006,
        "text": "Greenhouse gases, like water vapor\nand carbon dioxide absorb this radiation"
    },
    {
        "index": 78,
        "start_time": 231006,
        "end_time": 232491,
        "text": "and speed up."
    },
    {
        "index": 79,
        "start_time": 232491,
        "end_time": 237573,
        "text": "These hotter, faster-moving molecules\nemit infrared radiation in all directions,"
    },
    {
        "index": 80,
        "start_time": 237573,
        "end_time": 240346,
        "text": "including back to Earth, warming it."
    },
    {
        "index": 81,
        "start_time": 240346,
        "end_time": 243338,
        "text": "Does all this molecular motion ever stop?"
    },
    {
        "index": 82,
        "start_time": 243338,
        "end_time": 245940,
        "text": "You might think that would happen\nat absolute zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 83,
        "start_time": 245940,
        "end_time": 247815,
        "text": "the coldest possible temperature."
    },
    {
        "index": 84,
        "start_time": 247815,
        "end_time": 250677,
        "text": "No one&#39;s ever managed to cool\nanything down that much,"
    },
    {
        "index": 85,
        "start_time": 250677,
        "end_time": 251998,
        "text": "but even if we could,"
    },
    {
        "index": 86,
        "start_time": 251998,
        "end_time": 256213,
        "text": "molecules would still move due to\na quantum mechanical principle"
    },
    {
        "index": 87,
        "start_time": 256213,
        "end_time": 258561,
        "text": "called zero-point energy."
    },
    {
        "index": 88,
        "start_time": 258561,
        "end_time": 262747,
        "text": "In other words, everything has been moving\nsince the universe&#39;s very first moments,"
    },
    {
        "index": 89,
        "start_time": 262747,
        "end_time": 266220,
        "text": "and will keep going long, \nlong after we&#39;re gone."
    }
]